items.title: Azerbaijan Airlines plane crashes in Kazakhstan, and more - Five stories you need to know | Reuters
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
1. South Korea's main opposition party said it will introduce a bill to impeach acting President Han Duck-soo on Thursday and hold a vote on Friday, a move that could deepen the country's constitutional crisis triggered by a short-lived martial law.

2. An Embraer passenger jet crashed near the city of Aktau in Kazakhstan on Wednesday, killing 38 people, after diverting from an area of Russia that Moscow has recently defended against Ukrainian drone attacks.

3. Russia's Federal Security Service said on Thursday it had foiled several plots by Ukrainian intelligence services to kill high-ranking Russian officers and their families in Moscow using bombs disguised as power banks or document folders.

4. Japan Airlines said on Thursday its systems returned to normal, with same-day ticket sales resuming, after a cyberattack delayed some domestic and international flights.

5. Survivors and families of victims of the Indian Ocean tsunami 20 years ago visited mass graves, lit candles and comforted one another across Southeast and South Asia in ceremonies on Thursday to mark the disaster that killed some 230,000 people.

items.title: 2024 in #Reuters pictures
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
Reuters sent out some 1.6 million pictures to the world in 2024, covering news and daily life, tragedies, chaos and customs, from 120 countries.

Roughly half the worldâ€™s population went out to vote in elections. Catastrophic floods hit Brazil, Kenya, North Carolina and Nepal. Prices rose, protests broke out, and grinding wars in Ukraine and the Middle East escalated.

There was violence in Haiti, wildfires in Greece, and another disputed election in Venezuela.

People sought relief in quiet prayer, art, and exercise. But they also came together to cheer on victories for their sporting teams or election candidates, to watch the moon cover the sun, and to celebrate love and family.

Photojournalists from Reuters were there to capture it all â€” and much more.

items.title: Azerbaijan Airlines plane crashes in Kazakhstan
items.author: Reuters
items.content:
**WARNING: GRAPHIC IMAGES** An Azerbaijan Airlines plane bursts into flames as it crashes into the ground with injured passengers seen stumbling from an intact piece of the fuselage.

The plane crashed near the city of Aktau in Kazakhstan on Dec. 25 killing 38, with 29 survivors being treated at a local hospital.

Azerbaijan Airlines flight J2-8243 had flown hundreds of miles off its scheduled route toÂ crashÂ on the opposite shore of the Caspian Sea, after what Russia's aviation watchdog said was an emergency that may have been caused by a bird strike. But an aviation expert suggested that cause seemed unlikely.

Officials did not immediately explain why it had crossed the sea, but theÂ crashÂ came shortly after drone strikes hit southern Russia. Drone activity has shut airports in the area in the past and the nearest RussianÂ airportÂ on theÂ plane's flight pathÂ was closed that morning.
